      "text": "For the next two to three weeks, the last traces of nicotine are leaving your system, and your brain is reabsorbing the receptors that the drug had multiplied. During this window you may notice the little monster: a faint, restless, something's-missing feeling, sometimes a flash of irritability, sometimes a craving sparked by a familiar moment. None of it is severe. It's an itch, not an injury.\n\nThe decisive factor isn't whether the feeling shows up — it's how you read it. A smoker on the willpower method reads that emptiness as \"I'm being deprived of something I want,\" and the misery snowballs. You're going to read the exact same sensation completely differently: \"That's the monster dying. That's the feeling of years of addiction draining out of me.\" Same physical signal, opposite meaning — and the meaning is what determines the suffering. This is one of the oldest truths in cognitive therapy: it isn't the event that distresses us, it's our interpretation of it."
