      "text": "When a craving rises today, you're going to surf it rather than fight it or feed it. A craving has a shape: it builds, it crests, and — if you don't act on it — it falls and passes, usually within about three minutes. It cannot grow forever, and it has no power to make your hand move. Your only job is to stay on the board while the wave rolls under you.\n\nHere's how, in the moment: notice the craving without alarm. Locate it physically — is it in your chest, your throat, your hands, your mood? Watch it the way you'd watch weather, with curiosity rather than dread. Breathe slowly. Name it: \"monster, hungry, dying.\" And let it crest and fall on its own. Each wave you ride without a puff is direct proof that you don't need to smoke — and it makes the next wave smaller. You're not enduring cravings; you're dissolving them."
